# Lab Name
Reflected XSS into attribute with angle brackets HTML-encoded

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – Reflected XSS

## Objective
Exploit a reflected XSS vulnerability where angle brackets are HTML-encoded but user input is reflected inside an HTML attribute.

## Entry Point
Search functionality

## Exploitation Type
Reflected XSS / Attribute Injection

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and locate the search functionality

2. Submit a normal search request

3. Observe that the search term is reflected inside an HTML attribute value

4. Notice that angle brackets (< and >) are HTML-encoded, preventing direct tag injection

5. Since the input is placed inside an attribute, inject a double quote to break out of the attribute value

6. Add a new event handler attribute containing JavaScript code

7. Submit the payload through the search parameter

8. Trigger the event by moving the mouse over the affected element

9. Observe that JavaScript executes successfully

## Payload Used

" onmouseover="alert(1)

## Result
Successfully executed arbitrary JavaScript by breaking out of an HTML attribute and injecting an event handler.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- Account compromise

## Mitigation
- Properly encode user input for HTML attributes
- Escape quotation marks and special characters
- Validate and sanitize user input
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Use secure templating frameworks

## Learning
HTML encoding angle brackets alone is not sufficient to prevent XSS.
When user input is reflected inside an HTML attribute, attackers may be able to inject new attributes and event handlers if quotation marks are not properly encoded.
